            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is the Harris-Benedict equation?</h2>
              <p>
                The Harris-Benedict equation is one of the most widely used
                formulas to estimate
                <strong>basal metabolic rate (BMR)</strong> — the number of
                calories your body burns at rest to maintain vital functions
                such as breathing, circulation and temperature regulation.
              </p>
              <p>
                Once BMR is known, it can be multiplied by an
                <strong>activity factor</strong> to estimate
                <em>total daily energy expenditure (TDEE)</em>, i.e. the
                calories you need to maintain your current weight.
              </p>

              <h3>Original Harris-Benedict (1918–1919)</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Men</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{BMR} = 66.47 + 13.75 \times \text{weight (kg)} + 5.003
                  \times \text{height (cm)} - 6.755 \times \text{age (years)}\)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2"><strong>Women</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{BMR} = 655.1 + 9.563 \times \text{weight (kg)} + 1.850
                  \times \text{height (cm)} - 4.676 \times \text{age (years)}\)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                These equations were derived from indirect calorimetry
                measurements in the early 20th century. Modern studies show they
                tend to <strong>slightly overestimate</strong> BMR for many
                people.
              </p>

              <h3>Revised Harris-Benedict (Roza &amp; Shizgal, 1984)</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Men</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{BMR} = 88.362 + 13.397 \times \text{weight (kg)} +
                  4.799 \times \text{height (cm)} - 5.677 \times \text{age
                  (years)}\)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2"><strong>Women</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{BMR} = 447.593 + 9.247 \times \text{weight (kg)} +
                  3.098 \times \text{height (cm)} - 4.330 \times \text{age
                  (years)}\)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The revised equations use updated data and generally provide
                <strong>better agreement</strong> with measured BMR in
                contemporary adults. Many clinical nutrition guidelines still
                reference them.
              </p>

              <h3>Mifflin-St Jeor (1990) for comparison</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Men and women</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{BMR} = 10 \times \text{weight (kg)} + 6.25 \times
                  \text{height (cm)} - 5 \times \text{age (years)} + s\)
                </p>
                <p>where \(s = 5\) for men and \(s = -161\) for women.</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Several validation studies suggest that Mifflin-St Jeor is often
                the <strong>most accurate</strong> equation for adults with
                normal or overweight BMI in outpatient settings. That is why
                this calculator shows it alongside Harris-Benedict.
              </p>

              <h2>From BMR to daily calorie needs</h2>
              <p>
                To estimate your total daily energy expenditure (TDEE), multiply
                BMR by an activity factor:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Sedentary</strong> (little or no exercise): \( \times
                  1.2 \)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Lightly active</strong> (1–3 days/week): \( \times
                  1.375 \)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Moderately active</strong> (3–5 days/week): \( \times
                  1.55 \)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Very active</strong> (6–7 days/week): \( \times 1.725
                  \)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Extra active</strong> (hard exercise or physical job):
                  \( \times 1.9 \)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Our calculator applies these factors automatically and also
                suggests approximate calorie targets for
                <strong>slow weight loss</strong>,
                <strong>moderate weight loss</strong> and
                <strong>slow weight gain</strong> based on your chosen formula.
              </p>

              <h2>Example calculation</h2>
              <p>
                Suppose a 35‑year‑old woman, 165 cm tall and 65 kg, moderately
                active:
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Revised Harris-Benedict BMR</strong><br />
                  \(\text{BMR} = 447.593 + 9.247 \times 65 + 3.098 \times 165 -
                  4.330 \times 35 \approx 1\,389\ \text{kcal/day}\)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Maintenance calories (TDEE)</strong><br />
                  Moderately active factor = 1.55<br />
                  \(\text{TDEE} \approx 1\,389 \times 1.55 \approx 2\,153\
                  \text{kcal/day}\)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Moderate weight loss target</strong><br />
                  ≈ 2,153 − 500 ≈ 1,650 kcal/day
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Limitations and clinical use</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  All predictive equations have
                  <strong>individual error</strong>, often ±5–15% or more.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Accuracy is lower in
                  <strong>very muscular, obese, elderly, critically ill</strong>
                  or <strong>pregnant</strong> individuals.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Indirect calorimetry remains the
                  <strong>gold standard</strong> for measuring resting energy
                  expenditure in clinical practice.
                </li>
                <li>
                  For therapeutic diets (e.g. undernutrition, obesity, ICU), use
                  this calculator only as a
                  <strong>starting estimate</strong> and follow professional
                  guidelines.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Which formula should I choose?</h3>
              <p>
                For most healthy adults, the
                <strong>revised Harris-Benedict</strong> or
                <strong>Mifflin-St Jeor</strong> equations are reasonable
                choices. If you want to align with many modern nutrition
                studies, Mifflin-St Jeor is often preferred; if you follow older
                clinical protocols, revised Harris-Benedict may match them
                better. Our comparison table lets you see the difference
                instantly.
              </p>

              <h3>How often should I recalculate my BMR?</h3>
              <p>
                Recalculate when your
                <strong>weight changes significantly</strong> (e.g. ±5–10% of
                body weight), when your <strong>activity level changes</strong>,
                or at least every few months during a structured nutrition or
                training program.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use this calculator for children or teenagers?</h3>
              <p>
                No. Harris-Benedict and Mifflin-St Jeor were developed for
                adults. For children and adolescents, use pediatric‑specific
                equations and growth charts, and consult a pediatrician or
                dietitian.
              </p>
